00:42:54.460 --> 00:42:56.250
with fiction?

00:42:56.250 --> 00:42:58.270
It ignores it.

00:42:58.270 --> 00:43:00.330
Fiction has been the
bastard stepchild

00:43:00.330 --> 00:43:05.530
of library collections
for 150 years.

00:43:05.530 --> 00:43:10.440
But let me give you two
experiences of reading fiction,

00:43:10.440 --> 00:43:13.520
particularly popular fiction.

00:43:13.520 --> 00:43:17.190
After her father died in 1963,

00:43:17.190 --> 00:43:21.560
9-year old Sonia Sotomayor
buried herself in reading

00:43:21.560 --> 00:43:24.430
at her Broncs library in
the apartment she shared

00:43:24.430 --> 00:43:27.060
with her mother and her brother.

00:43:27.060 --> 00:43:30.770
Nancy Drew had a powerful hold on
my imagination, she remembered.

00:43:30.770 --> 00:43:34.400 position:56%
Every night, when I finished reading
and got into bed and closed my eyes,

00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:39.060
I'd continue the story with me in
Nancy's shoes until I fell asleep.

00:43:39.060 --> 00:43:42.910
Her mind, she noted, worked in
ways very similar to Nancy's.

00:43:42.910 --> 00:43:44.970
I was a keen observer and listener.

00:43:44.970 --> 00:43:46.270
I picked up on clues.

00:43:46.270 --> 00:43:49.570
I figured things out logically
and I enjoyed puzzles.

00:43:49.570 --> 00:43:53.110
I loved the clear, focused feeling
that came when I concentrated

00:43:53.110 --> 00:43:58.010
on solving a problem and
everything else faded out.

00:43:58.010 --> 00:44:03.270
Every single female Supreme Court
member read Nancy Drew as a kid.

00:44:03.270 --> 00:44:06.280
Nancy Drew never shows
up in the bibliographies

00:44:06.280 --> 00:44:08.410
